[11.720386, "o", "\u001b[90m2026-04-23 16:48:59.632\u001b[0m | \u001b[32minfo    \u001b[m | \u001b[35m         Device\u001b[0m | \u001b[37mClosing user mode device drivers\u001b[0m \u001b[90m(tt_cluster.cpp:478)\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[90m2026-04-23 16:48:59.632\u001b[0m | \u001b[32minfo    \u001b[m | \u001b[35m            UMD\u001b[0m | \u001b[37mClosing devices in cluster\u001b[0m \u001b[90m(cluster.cpp:962)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[12.534055, "o", "\r\n"]
[14.535131, "o", "─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\r\nThat's the hardware thinking. Real RISC-V cores. Real game text.\r\n\r\nThe wall: the Zork opening needs ~400 instructions total.\r\nAt 10 per batch, that's 40+ batches. The per-batch device\r\nopen/close overhead (~0.5 s each) makes it slow but workable.\r\n\r\nWhat can't be fixed in Python: the firmware watchdog itself.\r\n"]
[14.535158, "o", "interpret(20+) hangs when PRINT fires — a firmware-level limit\r\non QB2 that only the TT-Metal team can address.\r\n\r\nThis is proof-of-concept, not a playable game. Stage 4 is.\r\n─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\r\n"]
